[35m│[0m - Thoughts: **Why This Worked**:                                             [35m│[0m
[35m│[0m - The application implements keyword-based filtering (blocks "OR") but not   [35m│[0m
[35m│[0m operator-based filtering                                                     [35m│[0m
[35m│[0m - SQLite/PostgreSQL `||` operator acts as OR in boolean contexts             [35m│[0m
[35m│[0m - The LIKE clause always evaluates to true when comparing '%' to '%',        [35m│[0m
[35m│[0m effectively bypassing the WHERE clause restriction                           [35m│[0m
[35m│[0m - The filter focuses on common SQL injection keywords but misses SQL         [35m│[0m
[35m│[0m operators                                                                    [35m│[0m
[35m│[0m                                                                              [35m│[0m
[35m│[0m **Filter Bypass Analysis**:                                                  [35m│[0m
[35m│[0m - ❌ Blocked: `' OR '1'='1` → 500 error (keyword "OR" detected)              [35m│[0m
[35m│[0m - ✅ Allowed: `' || '1'='1` → Empty result (but no error - filter bypassed)  [35m│[0m
[35m│[0m - ✅ Allowed: `' || '%' LIKE '%` → All records returned (successful bypass)  [35m│[0m
[35m│[0m                                                                              [35m│[0m
[35m│[0m **Security Implications**:                                                   [35m│[0m
[35m│[0m - Keyword-based allowlists are insufficient for SQL injection prevention     [35m│[0m
[35m│[0m - Parameterized queries should be used instead of string concatenation       [35m│[0m
[35m│[0m - Access control should be enforced in application logic, not SQL queries    [35m│[0m
[35m│[0m - The `||` operator can act as OR in SQLite, bypassing keyword filters       [35m│[0m
